Taking inspiration from the anti-immigrant and patriotic movements of the early 19th Century such as the Know Nothings, the flag combines a portrait of Washington flanked by 13 star American flags with an eagle perched atop carrying a shield with the president's family coat of arms. One of the more interesting elements of the flag is the phrase "Native Americans Beware of Foreign Influence", which boldly asserts the nativity of the European people on this continent, especially since the term "Native Americans" was not popularized in reference to Indians until the mid-20th Century. Likewise it must be understood that while Patriot Front endorses the nationalist and nativist principles of the movements from which the banner is derived, it does not share many of the religious opinions commonly associated. Harrison was resolute that Northwest Territories become the home of American prosperity and of the westward marching European race, asking â€œIs one of the fairest portions of the globe to remain in a state of nature, the haunt of a few wretched savages, when it seems destined by the Creator to give support to a large population and to be the seat of civilization?â€ With the Indians unable to stand against the Americans alone, they invited the support of the British Empire, who had long funded and armed the rebellious tribes. William Henry Harrison cautiously navigated Indian protests over American expansion in the regions under his governorship. Notably warning the tempestuous tribes that "our Blue Coats are more numerous than you can count, and our hunting shirts are like the leaves of the forests or the grains of sand on the Wabash." Force was the only language left after diplomacy failed, and would decide the destiny of the nations. With Tecumseh away riling more tribes against the Americans, his capitol lay undefended. Harrison's army was ambushed outside the Indian city, and a fierce battle started in which the Americans emerged bloodied yet victorious. The "Great Spirit" failed to protect the Indian warriors as the shamans claimed, and scores were sent to their "happy hunting grounds" alongside their ancestors. Harrison and his troops razed the capitol of the Indian confederacy and dug up the graves of its burial grounds in retribution. [2/3] ğŸ“ William Henry Harrison Monument, Cincinnati, Ohio

During the War of 1812, Britain sought to ally itself with the Indian war chief Tecumseh to create an independent tribal government in what is now the Midwest. Tecumseh's proposed dominion would be a buffer state to guard British interests against the territorial expansion of Americans across the virgin lands of the continent. Tecumseh's war was the third time a vast collection of tribal nations would ally themselves with an imperialist power to check the expansion of the rapidly growing stock of America. First in the French and Indian War, secondly in the Revolutionary War, and finally in the War of 1812. Each time resulted in the defeat of the Indians and their allies, and the indomitable progress of Manifest Destiny. [1/3] ğŸ“ William Henry Harrison Monument, Cincinnati, Ohio

Built in 1876 in Boston, the Essex was part of America's effort to create a fleet on par with the great powers of Europe. Hosting an auxiliary steam engine, and three masts, she was one of the first steam capable ships in the United States Navy, and one of the last primarily sail powered ships in the fleet. The Essex held active service until 1904, and was a training vessel until 1930. The Essex was then stripped of components, towed into Lake Superior, and given a fiery funeral with hundreds of gallons of kerosene. Nothing remains of the vessel save for the steam piping that survived the blaze, and is still visible today on Minnesota's coast. ğŸ“Minnesota Point, Minnesota

Lucius Quinctius Cincinnatus was born in 519 BC, and became a legendary figure of Roman civic virtue. He is depicted in this monument returning to a life of agrarian simplicity after having assumed sole authority of the Roman Republic during an invasion, which he repelled and defeated. With one hand he returns the fasces, a symbol of the republic's authority, and with the other he holds the plow of his farm and civilian life. Cincinnati, Ohio was named by Arthur Saint Clair in 1790, who was a member of the Society of The Cincinnati, a hereditary order of Revolutionary War officers who venerated Washington as the modern Cincinnatus, a man who assumed near-total authority to repel a foreign threat, then retired to his farm, returning power to the grateful nation. Washington is also depicted in famous statues holding a plow and fasces. The statue of Cincinnatus is the largest in the world, and the only one to depict him holding a fasces. ğŸ“Cincinnati, Ohio

James Butler "Wild Bill" Hickok may have picked up the nickname â€œWild Billâ€ for his daring fighting in the Union army during the Civil War, which included service as a spy, a scout, and a sharpshooter. After the war Hickok continued his adventurous ways, at times just skirting the right side of the law. James Butler "Wild Bill" Hickok, in 1858 joined the Russell, Majors, and Waddell Freight Company which later became the Pony Express, an express mail service that used relays of horse-mounted riders to transport mail back and forth between Missouri and California. While driving the freight team from Missouri to New Mexico, Hickok encountered a black bear with her two cubs. Protective of its cubs, the bear attacked Hickok, crushing his body and coming close to biting through the gunslinger's arm. For his part, Hickok attempted to kill the bear with his revolver, but his bullets ricocheted off the bear and angered it further. According to the legend, Hickok then engaged the bear in hand-to-hand combat, and finally defeated it by slitting its throat. The incident left him bedridden for the next few months. In 1815 Elizabeth Patton married Davy Crockett. In the mid 1850's, many years after Crockett's death at The Battle of The Alamo in 1836, she moved her family from Tennessee to the Acton area to claim a 320 acre land grant offered by the Republic of Texas to the defenders of The Alamo. Elizabeth died in 1860 and was buried in the black gown of a widow she had worn upon hearing of her husband's death. In 1911 a monument was placed atop her grave. She is sculpted atop a pillar looking south, awaiting her husband's return from the war. American morale was rekindled. Militias sallied into the field once more and struck at British forces in hit-and-run attacks. Recruits streamed into the Continental Army, and victory had been snatched from the jaws of defeat. Frederick The Great, then king of Prussia, is reported to have said that the Trenton campaign was the most brilliant campaign of the century. The impact of the American Revolution did not end there. The German-born American Emanuel Leutze painted "Washington Crossing the Delaware" in 1851, just three years after a revolution failed to unite the 39 states of the German Confederacy. In doing so, he voiced his mutual support for the American cause, and its example in Europe. The exact details of the painting have been argued, but the daring resolve and high courage captured in that image are uncontested. His depiction of the event would become one of the most impactful and significant American icons of the Revolution. [4/4] ğŸ¨ Emanuel Leutze, Washington Crossing The Delaware, 1851

The attack crashed into the Hessian camp in the morning light. The leader of the German mercenaries was killed as he attempted to rally his men. The British response to this defeat was immediate and severe. Seven thousand troops started at once to crush Washington's twenty four hundred. They camped opposite a creek north of Trenton, sure of their position and a victory the following day. Washington again evaded and outsmarted superior positioned and armed opponents, left his fires burning and slipped away to Princeton where he defeated and routed another British detachment. [3/4] ğŸ¨ Emanuel Leutze, Washington Crossing The Delaware, 1851

Washington's plans had been revealed to the Hessians by a spy in his ranks. Cowardly deserters would accept amnesty in exchange for similar information on the American army's movements. Due to luck, and the perceived impossibility of the attack the turncoats had reported, there was no considerable response by the enemy. This was not unfounded, either, as every one of Washington's division commanders failed to engage the plans given to him. Washington was alone in his efforts, only his skill and tact lying between victory and defeat. Every boat and barge had been collected from the river, and experienced fishermen prepared to guide the soldiers through the perilous conditions of a winter storm from the northeast which lashed the men with ice and wind. John Sullivan sent word to Washington on the march that his soldier's muskets were wet, and could not fire, Washington replied: "Use the bayonet, for the town must be taken." [2/4] ğŸ¨ Emanuel Leutze, Washington Crossing The Delaware (Detail), 1851

On the night of December 25th, Washington crossed the Delaware. A week prior Thomas Paine had wrote to the soldiers "Tyranny, like hell, is not easily conquered; yet we have this consolation with us, that the harder the conflict, the more glorious the triumph." Washington's objective was to assault the Hessian forces outside Trenton. The Revolution was in dire straits. Washington's army had been driven from New York, now occupied by the enemy. Men deserted the Continental ranks daily to return to their workshops and farms. The nation's cause was left with a few thousand ragged soldiers saved only by their rapid withdrawals from the Imperial advance. British General Howe took up quarters in New York, and waited for the Americans to crumble. Without a decisive victory, the Revolution would die a slow death. [1/4] ğŸ¨ Thomas Sully, The Passage of The Delaware (Detail), 1819

Texas joined the United States a decade after the fall of Fort Parker. Two decades pass, and "the hardy pioneers have pushed the frontier of civilization far to the north and west, driving the Indian and the buffalo before them. The scene of Parker's fort is now in the heart of a dense population; farms, towns, churches and school houses lie along the path by which the Indians marched from their camp in that bloody May of 1836." Cynthia Ann Parker would remain among the Indians for twenty four years, be wed to the chief Nocona, and bear the son Quanah Parker, the last chief of the free Comanches. [6/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

Rachel Plummer, captive eighteen months, tells the story of her six month old infant, born six months into her captivity. "One of the Indians caught my child by the throat and strangled it until, to all appearances, it was dead." She says, "I exerted all my feeble strength to save my child, but the other Indians held me fast. The Indian who had strangled the child then threw it up in the air repeatedly and let it fall upon the frozen ground until life seemed to be extinct [...] I had been weeping incessantly whilst they were murdering my child, but now my grief was so great that the fountain of my tears dried up." Rachel manages to resuscitate her child, but "as soon as the Indians ascertained that the child was still alive, they tore it from my arms, and knocked me down. They tied a plaited rope around its neck and threw it into a bunch of prickly pears and then pulled it backwards and forwards until its tender flesh was literally torn from its body." [5/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

The band would receive immediate aid from the fort thanks to Parker, and a party would return to bury the dead left at the site of the massacre. "Unadorned are their graves, not even a slab of marble or a memento of any kind has been erected to tell the traveler where rest the remains of this brave little band of pioneer heroes who wrestled with the savage for the mastery of this broad domain." writes Texan historian Wilbarger. The strife was over for them, but the privations of those captured by the Comanche had only just begun. The braves brought their captives together just after the assault on the fort, and lashed them together with raw hide ropes so tightly that their flesh was cut open, "gathering around with their yet bloody, dripping scalps, commenced their usual war dance. They danced, screamed, yelled stamping on their prisoners, beating them with bows until their own blood came close to strangling them." [4/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

"From the tracks of the Indians on the high lands it was evident they were hunting us," Parker states "we concluded it best to take to the river bottom again, for though the brambles might tear our flesh they might at the same time save our lives by hiding us from the cruel savages who were in pursuit of us The briars did in fact tear the legs and feet of the children until they could have been tracked by the blood that flowed from their wounds." The band of survivors treks on, weary and without food. Parker manages to feed the group meagerly with skunks and tortoises captured and killed by hand. He leaves a man in charge of the band and rushes alone to Fort Houston after it is certain that the women and children can go no further. "I had not eaten a mouthful of food for six days, having always given my share of the animals mentioned to the children," Parker says, yet he managed to travel the remaining thirty five miles to Fort Houston in a single day. [3/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

Later that year, as simple life at the fort resumed, these families in the "advance guard of civilization" would face a horde of five hundred Comanche and Kiowa. The Indians feigned peaceful intent with a white flag, then surrounded and killed the envoy sent from the fort, before attacking the fort as they uttered "the most terrific and unearthly yells that ever greeted the ears of mortals". Many were killed and captured and the rest fled towards the nearest settlement of Fort Houston, over ninety miles away on foot. "We were truly a forlorn set, many of us barefooted and bareheaded, a relentless foe on the one hand and on the other a trackless and uninhabited wilderness infested with reptiles and wild beasts, entirely destitute of food and means of procuring it." Says Mr. Parker, who survived the attack and led the survivors East, "I took one of my children on my shoulder and led another. The grown persons followed my example and we began our journey." [2/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

In 1833 nine families from Illinois formed a settlement on the Navasota river in Texas. There they constructed Fort Parker, named after the Parker family among them "to secure themselves against the various tribes of roving savages". For two years the colonists lived a life of "Arcadian simplicity", "engaged in the avocations of a rural life", but in 1835 they were compelled to abandon their fort in an escape from the invading armies of Mexicans that came with Santa Anna. They would remain exiled until the following year when "the sudden and unexpected news reached them that Santa Anna and his vandal hordes had been confronted and defeated at San Jacinto, that sanguinary engagement which gave birth to the new sovereignty of Texas, and that Texas was free from Mexican tyranny". [1/6] ğŸ“Fort Parker Reconstruction, Groesbeck, Texas

He killed several hundred Spaniards and forced the rest from the region for over a decade. It would prove later that PopÃ© overstepped by not only waging war against the European settlers, but also their innovations as he ordered the removal of all Spanish tools and goods from use. This involved returning to obscure, esoteric tribal languages, and reverting from the standard calendar. The resulting discontent would see Santa Fe again return into Spanish hands once again under the new Governor, Diego de Vargas. Washington's plan relied on French expeditionary forces under the command of Lt. General Rochambeau. The largest of the ships under his command was the Ville De Paris, armed with over 100 guns. The French fleet won the Battle of The Chesapeake, allowing them to blockade the British in the captured city of Yorktown. The siege was characterized by the entrenchments on both sides, with American lines inching their way to the walls of the British fortifications as artillery barrages decimated the ships and redoubts of the increasingly desperate Lord Cornwallis who, after three weeks of bombardment, realized no reinforcements would reach him. Upon the inevitable surrender, Cornwallis could not bring himself to face defeat with cordial honors, so sent one of his officers in his place, claiming illness. The liberation of Yorktown had broken the back of the British war effort in America and vindicated the bloodshed of patriots throughout the revolution. ğŸ“Yorktown Victory Monument, Yorktown, Virginia

The Battle of Yorktown was the culmination of the American Revolution. General George Washington moved to surround the dug-in Lord Cornwallis on the Virginia coast with the help of land and sea elements of the French Special Expedition. The Continental Army would march from New York, while the French would march from Rhode Island, They would traverse over 600 miles in the summer months of 1781 in only 98 days. The march proceeded at a grueling pace with consideration to the quantity of equipment, and the quality of the roads. The destination of the march was kept strictly secret, even false dispatches were sent to confuse British spy networks, and rumors proliferated among the American camp. The Ulster County Gazette, A New York Newspaper would later cite the following exchange between Washington and an unnamed camp aide â€œSir, the men are placing bets over where we are marching, New York or Richmond.â€ to which Washington replied: â€œGood, let them place bets.â€ ğŸ“Yorktown Victory Monument, Virginia

The wonder rests on land previously used as a staging area for soldiers in both The War of 1812 and The Civil War. The Parthenon pays tribute to Athena, daughter of Zeus and hailed as the goddess of wisdom. Inside the temple, which is a replica equal in size to its Grecian counterpart, the largest indoor sculpture in The West is housed. Athena stands tall at 42 feet and holds Nike, godess of Victory, in her palm. In 1889, President Benjamin Harrison was to open two million acres of Oklahoma to American settlement. The lands, previously withheld as Indian Territory, drew large crowds to camps in nearby cities as they waited for Harrison's proclamation to come into effect. Through the Homestead Act of 1862, a settler could claim 160 acres of federal, public land, and by living and improving the land for five years, recieve a title of formal ownership. Impoverished farmers, cowboys, prospectors, and laborers filled the ranks of the wagon trains trailing into Eastern Oklahoma. Borderlands in Texas, Arkansas, and Kansas were inundated with the massive influx of anxious homesteaders. At the moment of the proclamation's effective status, cannons, rifles, and military bugles were sounded above the aspiring crowds. These settlers would form the communities that would pave the way for Oklahoma's American statehood. ğŸ“Oklahoma Land Run Monument, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma

The Cumberland Compact outlined a simple, representative civil body for the 248 signers to settle on the harsh frontier on the Western reaches of American civilization. The Compact formed a militia that consisted of all men, of fighting shape, over the age of 16. In 1780, in the small but fortified settlement of Nashborough, this document would be signed into law. Four years later, a third of the signers would be dead as a result of attacks by the Tribal Nations. After a brutal decade of conflict, the lands would be civilized and opened to larger settlement and Westward Expansion. The document remained in effect until Tennessee was granted statehood in 1796. ğŸ“Nashville, Tennessee

In 1913, the United Mine Workers of America successfully unionized in the Colorado Front Range. In doing so, they met their employers with a number of demands. The Great Chicago fire consumed two thousand acres of the city's landscape over the span of several days. Hundreds were killed by the blaze and over a hundred thousand left homeless. Chicago was placed under martial law as the damage was surveyed, and efforts to rebuild began with cities and communities nationwide offering supplies and support. A note in the Chicago Tribune, published a day after the fire had gone out, read: "In the midst of a calamity without parallel in the world's history, looking upon the ashes of thirty year's accumulations, the people of this once beautiful city have resolved that Chicago shall rise again." Two decades later, a renewed Chicago would host the World's Columbian Exposition with visitors from dozens of nations and over twenty million attendees. ğŸ“Michigan Avenue Bridge, Chicago, Illinois

Potter County, named after Robert Potter, lies in the Texas panhandle with Amarillo as its seat. Potter was born in North Carolina in 1800, and served in the North Carolina House of Commons before moving west as an activist for Texan Independence. His actions in the war for independence culminated in his signing of the Texan declaration. During the Regulator-Moderator War, an east Texas conflict that consumed several border counties over land disputes and cattle rustling, Potter lead Harrison County Moderators before his untimely death at the hands of a band of Regulators. The war would continue after his death for another two to five years, after the militants settled their disputes to serve in the Mexican American War. Decades later in 1876, the county would be named in his honor. ğŸ“Potter County Courthouse, Amarillo, Texas

Fort Roberdeau was constructed in 1778 during the Revolution and remained occupied by patriot militia until 1780. The fort was originally constructed by Daniel Roberdeau to protect the vital Pennsylvanian lead mining industry from attacks by the Tribal Nations and Loyalists. The lead deposits in Pennsylvania's Sinking Valley region supplied the Continental Army's war effort. Archeologists uncovered the fort's original foundations in 1939 with motivations to rebuild the site after concerned citizens cleared the site of overgrowth, yet the advent of World War II discontinued efforts to unearth and restore the remains. It would not be until the American Bicentennial that historical records would be consulted to restore Fort Roberdeau's stockades and buildings to their original prominence. ğŸ“Blair County, Pennsylvania

url_description: This talk sets out to refute the ideological pillars sustaining Canadian multiculturalism. The historical demographic evidence does not support the claim that "Canada is a nation of immigrants" but shows instead that Canada was founded by European settlers and by native-born Canadiens. The theory of multicultural citizenship is bedevilled by a double standard in granting both collective rights and individual rights to minorities and immigrant groups while suppressing the ethno-cultural rights of Euro-Canadians. Nevertheless, insomuch as this Charter, and the Multiculturalism Act of 1988, use the language of collective rights to guarantee the cultural identity of ethnic and religious minorities, this Charter and this Act can be relied upon to affirm the right of all Canadians, including EuroCanadians, to preserve and enhance their ethnic and cultural heritage. Members of the majority culture should not be excluded from affirming their right to collective survival in the face of immigration patterns that are threatening their cultural heritage in Canada. Ricardo Duchesne is a Canadian historical sociologist and professor at the University of New Brunswick. url_title: Critical Reflections on Canadian Multiculturalism w/ Prof. Ricardo Duchesne
url_description: This talk sets out to refute the ideological pillars sustaining Canadian multiculturalism. The historical demographic evidence does not support the claim that "Canada is a nation of immigrants" but shows instead that Canada was founded by European settlers and by native-born Canadiens. The theory of multicultural citizenship is bedevilled by a double standard in granting both collective rights and individual rights to minorities and immigrant groups while suppressing the ethno-cultural rights of Euro-Canadians. The concept of "minority rights" has been deceptively used by cultural Marxists to promote an illiberal program of mass immigration. New scientific studies support the view that humans generally have a preference for their ethnic in-groups, and that such altruistic dispositions as sharing, loyalty, caring, and trust are exhibited primarily within in-groups rather than toward a universal â€œweâ€ in disregard for oneâ€™s community. Canada's Charter of Rights and Freedoms (1982) was heavily influenced by supranational human rights principles detached from Canada's shared Anglo-Quebecois culture, religion, and ethnicity. Nevertheless, insomuch as this Charter, and the Multiculturalism Act of 1988, use the language of collective rights to guarantee the cultural identity of ethnic and religious minorities, this Charter and this Act can be relied upon to affirm the right of all Canadians, including EuroCanadians, to preserve and enhance their ethnic and cultural heritage. Members of the majority culture should not be excluded from affirming their right to collective survival in the face of immigration patterns that are threatening their cultural heritage in Canada. Ricardo Duchesne is a Canadian historical sociologist and professor at the University of New Brunswick. His main research interests are Western civilization, the rise of the West, and the ideology of diversity. In his 2011 main work The Uniqueness of Western Civilization he emphasizes the "continuous creativity" of Europeans from ancient Greek times to the present and criticises what he sees as the destructive effects of multiculturalism on modern Western culture. His last book, "Canada in Decay: Mass Immigration, Diversity, and the Ethnocide of Euro-Canadians," argues that Canada is not a "nation of immigrants" but a nation created by Anglo and French pioneers and settlers. "Canada in Decay" also questions the double standards of multiculturalism in granting both "collective" ethnic rights and "individual rights" to minorities and immigrant groups while suppressing the ethno-cultural rights of Euro-Canadians

T H E L A F A Y E T T E Entrepreneur Larry Imig began construction on this Colonial-style, boutique hotel in 1943, making it the only US hotel constructed during World War II. It opened on July 1, 1946, as Imig Manor and attracted Hollywood stars from the start â€” Bob Hope was the first guest. During its early days, other Hollywood stars like Frank Sinatra, Ava Gardner, Katherine Hepburn, and Bing Crosby checked in (and those are just the confirmed ones). The fun didnâ€™t last forever: In 1955, Conrad Hilton (owner of the San Diego Chargers) bought the hotel, changed its name, and used it as office space. For decades after, there were management changes and talks of demolition, but locals never lost that loving feeling for the hotel, especially when it got a cameo in â€œTop Gun.â€ After a $4 million renovation in 2012, it was added to the National Register of Historic Places. This generally is going to be put on the older generations, and as the youth grow old, they must then take up this role. Those of us that have assets like land, housing, or a business must use it to help our activists. If we donâ€™t support these men, we will have no one to fight for our land, and slowly our movement will lose relevance, and the flame of the European spirit will be extinguished.â€œI have learned what this term â€œbrotherhoodâ€ means in the truest sense. The officer on duty came by and knocked on the cell door grunting the word â€œmailâ€ through the tray slot. cleaned_message: What ought to be done about this? How do we prevent it? Well on the individual level you and I can do very little. Even if you think I'm wrong about my prognosis, it remains that it will be true for some and you should be on guard lest it happen to you. How do we go about preventing this? First, if you are on the Dissident Right like myself, start meaning it when you talk about building up alternative institutions and intentional communities. Get plugged into an appropriate group of likeminded men who build you up instead of tearing you down. Second, any good political movement starts at home, so think smaller while not leaving the bigger picture behind. Helping shape the trajectory of your hometown should be just as important to you as knowing what's going on in the middle east. Second, regarding politics, instantiate yourself as an individual in control of his own life. Recognize that you will never please the crowd of people no matter how much you throw your life into meat grinder of their judgmental demands. If they have a good idea and you like the cut of what they're saying, fine. But never forget that it is your life, not theirs, to live. We all like to emphasize the collective, and this is perfectly fine! But you are still an individual in that collective, and you have your own lifestyle choices to make; if you are entirely enmeshed into their way of doing things, you will suffer and have no one to blame but yourself. Third, especially applying to Christians, you need to realize that there is far more to Christianity than politics. It's not about being based or not, even though a Christian polity is objectively more ordered, masculine, and moral than what we have today â€“ it's a good thing to seek! Even so, there is more to this life than banging your head on the political wall. Apply the teachings of the Word to ALL spheres of your life, rather than just this one facet, and you will find yourself standing on the Christ our solid Ground instead of the sinking sands of movementrianism. Fourth, again applying to Christians specifically, never forget the Gospel. The draft, which was in effect from 1940 to 1975, was to fill slots that were not filled by regular recuiting. The amount at any given time needed varied from depends on how many volunteers would show up. You would get a draft notice with a date and location to appear. All your affairs had to be in order as if you could not provide an adequate reason for deferment you leave directly for basic training. Men would lose jobs, houses, cars, etc, as they wouldn't be able to make payments with that new E-1 private salary. This is a major issue that would have to be addressed that I have not heard brought up by anyone pushing for the draft. I would assume that this process would happen at MEPS (military entrance and processing station). MEPS's purpose is, in part, to turn away potential recruits. ASVAB, physical fitness, medical suitablity, and legal issuses are all things that they screen for. The majority of the population at risk of receiving a draft notice would be turned away at this stage. We live in an incredibly unhealthy society and the system, if it even acknowledges this will certainly not move to solve that problem. The whole MEPS process takes a couple of days. They put you up in a hotel in whatever town you happen to be in, and you can just walk out. Outside of every base, they will have to implement an active military police patrol again, restrict off-base liberty, and not allow civilian attire, and require servicemen to carry leave papers on them at all times like in the old days. Additionally, anyone who has been an NCO in the past decade knows that the way the Army handles hazing charges any drafted private could jam up a command by crying hazing, and with the internet you best believe dudes will be sharing the best ways to juke the system with a quickness. To reinstate the draft would require a reorientation of the military and society at large to implement. Tldr you're not getting drafted because doing so would break the Army.
